{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Should You Attend?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"You don't have to attend personally, but it's often helpful:"}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can the tenant stop the eviction on the day?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Only if they have a court order suspending or setting aside the warrant. A last-minute promise to pay or emotional appeal won't stop the bailiff. Once they arrive with a valid warrant, the eviction proceeds."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What time do bailiffs arrive?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Usually between 9am and 5pm. You'll typically be given a morning or afternoon slot rather than an exact time. Bailiffs often have multiple appointments and may not be precisely on time."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Do I have to pay for the bailiff?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"You pay the court fee for the warrant (£130). The bailiff service itself is included. If forced entry requires a locksmith, you may pay additional costs. Lock changes are your responsibility regardless."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What if there are children or vulnerable people?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Bailiffs are trained to handle these situations sensitively. They may contact social services or allow extra time. The eviction still proceeds, but with appropriate care for vulnerable occupants."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I use High Court Enforcement instead?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, you can \"transfer up\" to High Court Enforcement Officers (HCEOs) for faster action. This costs more but HCEOs typically execute warrants within days rather than weeks. They're also perceived as more efficient."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What if the tenant returns after eviction?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Once evicted, the tenant has no right to return. If they break in, it's criminal trespass and potentially burglary. Call the police. You do not need a new court order—the existing possession order remains valid."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Need Help With the Eviction Process?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Our Complete Eviction Pack guides you through every step, from notice to bailiff enforcement. Includes all forms, court documents, and step-by-step instructions."}}]}

